            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shay Miller\u2019s story begins not in the fog of San Francisco, but under the vast, clear skies of the Navajo Nation in Arizona. Raised by her mother and grandmother, her childhood was a blend of ancient tradition and modern reality. She learned the power of storytelling from her grandmother\u2019s Din\u00e9 legends and the art of hospitality from her mother, whose kitchen was the heart of their community, always filled with the aroma of frybread and stew for family and visitors alike. This duality\u2014honoring the past while navigating the present\u2014would become the cornerstone of her identity.\n\nLured by the promise of a broader world, Shay moved to San Francisco in her early twenties, enrolling in Hospitality Management at SF State. However, the structured pace of academia couldn't compete with the adrenaline of a part-time job she took with a high-end caterer. She discovered her true classroom was in the controlled chaos of a frantic kitchen and the graceful execution of a flawless event. She left college before graduating, a decision that worried her family but felt instinctively right. It was a gamble that paid off; her work ethic and innate talent for organization saw her rise steadily through the city\u2019s competitive events industry.\n\nA key turning point came a decade ago when she was hired as the Catering and Events Director for a major downtown arts center. Here, her disparate worlds merged. She orchestrated glamorous galas, complex donor receptions, and avant-garde performance art after-parties. Shay doesn\u2019t just manage logistics; she curates experiences, viewing each event as a story to be told through food, lighting, and flow.\n\nNow 51, Shay lives a life of disciplined routine. Her mornings begin in her cozy Inner Sunset apartment before she boards the N Judah streetcar for her 4.5-mile commute. Her days are a whirlwind, but she finds peace in walking through Golden Gate Park or sharing a bottle of wine with her tight-knit circle of friends, her chosen family. San Francisco is unequivocally home, a city whose diversity and creative spirit mirror her own. Shay dreams of one day launching her own consultancy, focusing on culturally significant events and mentoring other Indigenous women breaking into the industry, ensuring other stories, like hers, are told with elegance and strength."
